x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.14, p.64 (1976)

x4freetext: Target Material Consisted of a Uniform Mixture of
Enriched Zr-90 As Zr-Oxide and Spectroscopically Pure
Cu-Oxide.  Zr-Oxide Contained 97.7% 90-Zr and Less Than
1% of Each of the Other Stable Isotopes.  The  Chemical
Purity of Zr-Oxide was 99.8%.  The Powdered Target was
Contained in a Thin Walled Aluminium Tube.
In Some Experiments Pure Zr-Oxide was Irradiated. (SEE
UNDER `METHOD`).
Mostly a Mixture of Zr-Oxide and Cu-O (FOR MONITORING)
Was Irradiated.
In Case of Y-Isotopes the Contributions of Zr-Parents
Were Determined by Means of Multiple Timed Chemical
Separations. For these Experiments Pure Zr-Oxide
Targets Without Cu-O were Used and the Zr-90(P,2PN)Y-88
Cross Sections were Used As Secondary Monitor.
In All Other Cases the Precursors had Been Measured
Directly.
This Reaction was Used As a Secondary Monitor in Those
Cases, Where Pure Zr-Oxide Without Cu-O Admixture was
Irradiated.

x4freetext: The Disintegration Rates at the End of the Irradiations
Were Calculated from the Observed Counting Rates by
Correcting For Decay, Counter Efficiency, Absorption,
Photon Abundance and Chemical Yield.
Errors Given Include Uncertainties Associated
With Decay Curve Analysis, Detector Efficiencies,
Published Uncertainties in Decay Schemes and Chemical
Yields.
2.  The Beam Energy is the Nominal Average Energy at  a
Given Cyclotron Radius, Estimated to have an
Uncertainty of +-2 MeV, Corrected For Energy Loss in
The Thin Target.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.13, p.1095 (1976)

x4freetext: Analogous Experiment with the Same Goals, But Using
The Much Heavier Target Nucleus Hg-202. The Results
Are Compared to the Present Ones.
The Main Goal of this Work was to Study Alpha-Particle
Emission from Definite Reactions. The Complex
Excitation Functions have Been Decomposed Into a
Component Due to Emission of One or Two Alpha-Particles
And a Component Due to the Emission of Individual
Nucleons. Excitation Energy Spectra For Alpha-Emission
Events are Derived. The Implications of the Results
On the Preequilibrium Model of Nuclear Reactions
Are Discussed.
Numerical Values For Total Alpha Emission are Deduced
And Separated Into Direct and Evaporation Part. The
Results are Compared to Those Calculated For the Hg-202
Data from the Publication Cited Under `Rel-Ref`.
Nekw
Some Corrections have Been Included by
CAJAD
Some Corrections For `Reaction`.
Subentries 007, 013 and 010 are Corrected
Last checking has been done.

x4freetext: The Formerly Quoted 28.5 Min Isomer of Y-84 had
Probably Been Assigned Wrongly. In the Meantime,
Besides the 37 Min State, Which was Measured Here,
There was Found a Low Spin State (1+) With a Half-Life
Of 4.6 Sec Which Decays Via B+ and Ec Transitions
To Sr-84. Since No Isomeric Transition was Found,
It is Unclear Which Isomer is the Ground State. It
Is Adopted by the Compiler That the Measured Cross
Section is Only Partial. (COMMENT BY THE COMPILER).
Due to the Experimental Conditions It was Assumed
That the Given Cross Section Contains a Contribution
From the Precursor Zr-84. (COMMENT BY THE COMPILER).
See Comment of CAJAD.
Isomeric Transition is Absent
-  Attention -
-By Compiler of CAJAD. According to ENSDF (94 YEAR)
37.Min Activity is Y-84-M Activity. Y-84-G has
Half-Life 4.6 Sec.
